            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "### On wrapper\n\nThere are existing wrappers for diagnostics, formatting, etc., but it seems to depend on `popularity Ã— complexity`. Since learning how to extend a table or create an autocmd is unavoidable for a feature-rich setup, I don't insist on a separate wrapper for this simple case.\n\n### On default behavior\n\nI agree with your point about flexibility. Also, such change would require worrying about receiving a proper response from the server, its capabilities, other quirks like:\n\n>```lua\n> -- Send a notification with empty settings, rust_analyzer pulls the\n> -- configuration using a `workspace/configuration` request.\n>```\n\n### On alternatives\n\nThis seems like something that could instead be added to docs when `lsp.ClientCapabilities` receive their own section. I understand that `:notify()` is one-way, but not without side-effects. So I think we would have to mention checking: supported requests, server and client capabilities. And the \"upper bound\" of client capabilities seems to be the only missing piece.",
